TEMPLATE 1: Ask Before You Pitch
Structure:
Hey {{first_name}}, [open-ended question as CTA]

You're [trigger/observation]. [Potential problem deriving from Observation]

[How product solves Problem]

PS- Relevant because_____
When to Use:
High-level decision-makers (C-suite, Directors, Senior Managers)
Creating curiosity and relevance quickly
Growing companies or organizations undergoing change
Why It Works:
Follows "3P" structure (Problem, Promise, Proof). Quickly identifies relevant challenge, suggests solution, provides context. Open-ended question encourages engagement without being pushy.
Example:
Hey Will, think this would help George & Anne?

You're hiring new sellers. Despite the same templates, some reps get results and others don't.

Lavender gives you a clearer picture on why things work. We've even see it identify clear personalization plays for the team to use.

Figured that be relevant w the new focus upmarket.

Let me know.


TEMPLATE 2: Poke The Bear
Structure:
Hey {{first_name}} ‚Äì [relevant first line] 

[poke the bear question]. 

We're helping companies like [case study company_name] achieve [outcome] in [timeframe] without [no good rotten thing].
When to Use:
B2B companies offering significant efficiency/productivity improvements
Addressing clear, measurable pain points
When you have strong case study proof
Why It Works:
Starts with relevant question about pain point
Introduces hypothetical solution
Provides social proof with case study
Quantifies results and timeframe
Emphasizes absence of negative aspects
Ends with open-ended question
Example:
Hey {{first_name}} ‚Äì How long does it usually take for your team to reply to leads?

What if you could respond instantly, get actionable suggestions, and make every reply more impactful?

We're helping companies like [case study company_name] book 2x more meetings in just 30 days, without wasting time drafting manual responses or missing critical follow-up opportunities.

Would this be something you're looking to solve as well?

Best,
%Signature%


TEMPLATE 3: Standard Go-To Sequence
Structure:
Hey {{first_name}} ‚Äì [recency waterfall or relevance-based first line]. 

Specifically, I think it could help you [AI-generated line]. 

If we could help you [messaging to be tested], would that be useful to you?
When to Use:
First touch in cold email campaigns
When you can leverage recent industry trends or events
Decision-makers in rapidly changing industries
Why It Works:
Combines three powerful elements: (1) Personalization with name, (2) Timeliness by referencing recent trends/events, (3) Specific, quantifiable value proposition. Quick to customize while maintaining consistent format.
Example:
Hey John ‚Äì With the recent uptick in remote work, I think our platform can help streamline your team's workflow. Could it reduce admin overhead by 15%?


TEMPLATE 4: Feedback Only
Structure:
Hey {{first_name}}, 

let me preface this by saying I'm not trying to sell you anything. 

I was hoping to get some feedback from you as someone I would normally sell to‚Ä¶ 

[Insert question for feedback].
When to Use:
Market research and intelligence gathering
Decision-makers using competitor products
Building rapport without sales pressure
Understanding switching factors
Why It Works:
Lowers defenses by explicitly stating "not selling"
Invites honest feedback about needs/pain points
Reveals decision-making factors
Creates opportunity for future tailored outreach
Works well for qualifying leads
Example:
Hey Will, I'm not trying to sell you anything. What would it take for you to consider switching from your current CRM?


TEMPLATE 5: Upfront Value
Structure:
"[here is "value offering] hope it was helpful"
When to Use:
When you've provided unsolicited but highly relevant information
Decision-makers in data-driven industries (VC, consulting, B2B services)
Industries where information is power
Why It Works:
Positions you as valuable resource without being pushy. Demonstrates investment of time/effort upfront, creating reciprocity. Casual ending invites engagement without pressure.
Example:
Here's a list of every founder at every company that just implemented HubSpot... I hope it was helpful.


TEMPLATE 6: Short-Trigger Based Outreach
Structure:
Relevant trigger (personalization), 
Validation + value prop, 
CTA.
When to Use:
Specific, actionable insights about prospect's business
Quick wins or improvements available
Digital marketing, web development, app design, social media
Why It Works:
Demonstrates relevance and research immediately
Provides social proof through success story
Presents clear value proposition
Soft, non-pushy call-to-action
Concise for busy decision-makers
Example:
G, saw that Reach's latest blog post doesn't include a Meta tag which can affect its online visibility.

{{client}} improved theirs by creating meta tags using ChatGPT.

Can I share how?


TEMPLATE 7: Pain Point + Case Study
Structure:
Hey {{first_name}}, 

how are you managing [pain point]? 

We help {{job title}} at [subniche] solve [pain point] by [offer].
When to Use:
Decision-makers with clear, quantifiable challenges
When you can demonstrate immediate value
Industries with measurable pain points
Why It Works:
Immediately identifies pain point, establishes relevance, provides concrete success example. Versatile across industries. Communicates tangible results quickly.
Example:
Hey Sam, how are you managing sales team inefficiencies? We helped ABC Corp achieve 25% faster deal closures in three months.


TEMPLATE 8: Leader Responsibilities
Structure:
{{First Name}} as a {{role}} leader, curious how {{responsibility}}. 

Either way, {{personalize}}!
When to Use:
Decision-makers in leadership positions
Addressing specific role responsibilities or challenges
Peer-to-peer interaction tone desired
Why It Works:
Personalizes by name and acknowledges role
Piques curiosity about specific responsibility
Offers tailored solution/valuable insight
Low-pressure ask for conversation
Shows research on recipient's role
Demonstrates relevance to likely pain point
Example:
Armand, as a Sales leader, curious how your reps prioritize which accounts to reach out to? If I can create a list for your team, would it be worth a conversation?


TEMPLATE 9: The Why Are You Paying?
Structure:
Subject line: "You're at a vending machine"

Body:
You're at a vending machine.
You see [Product].
Three options ‚Äì $0, $1, or $1.50 for a [product].
What would you choose? Zero, right?

Then why are you paying [Competitor's rate]% in [related service] fees when you could be paying nothing?

Signature:
[Your Name]
[Your Position]
[Contact Information]
When to Use:
Clear cost-saving opportunity exists
Significantly better value proposition vs current solution
Industries where cost-saving is primary concern
Cost difference is significant and easy to quantify
Why It Works:
Uses relatable analogy to illustrate illogical nature of overpaying. Makes prospect question current spending habits. Particularly powerful when offering provides clear cost advantage.
Example:
Subject line: "You're at a vending machine"

Body:
You see Diet Coke.
Three options ‚Äì $0, $1, or $1.50 for a can.
What would you choose? Zero, right?

Then why are you paying Stripe 1.5% in international processing fees when you could be paying nothing?

Signature:
Leif [Last Name]
Global Account Executive
[Contact Information]


TEMPLATE 10: Short with Impact
Structure:
Hey {firstname} - curious if you're open to chat re: [business function] strategy? 

[Similar customer] was able to [quantifiable outcome], saw a reduction in [pain point] and [positive outcome] using [process]. 

If it makes sense Q4, should we set up a call? 

Thanks -{sender initials}
When to Use:
Mid to large-sized companies
Decision-makers facing efficiency/growth challenges
Versatile, high-impact B2B outreach
Why It Works:
Follows AIDA principle (Attention, Interest, Desire, Action) in concise format. Grabs attention with personalized opener, piques interest with similar customer, creates desire with quantifiable outcomes, prompts action with call suggestion.
Example:
Subject: Growth opportunity

Hey {{first_name}} - curious if you're open to chat re: SDR workflow strategy? Similar customers were able to boost their conversion rates by 30%, saw a reduction in response times, and increased meeting bookings using a Clay table connected to Slack for real-time notifications. If it makes sense for Q4, should we set up a call?

Thanks,
-%Sender Initials%


TEMPLATE 11: Lead Magnet Approach
Structure:
Hey {{first_name}} ‚Äì I saw [something relevant]. 

We help companies achieve [results]. 

I made you a [resource].
When to Use:
Decision-makers in growth-oriented companies
Professionals actively expanding services or expertise
When you can offer immediate, tailored value
Why It Works:
Shows you've done homework
Briefly states value proposition
Offers relevant resource upfront
Subtly showcases expertise
Request for feedback opens natural conversation
Example:
Hey James ‚Äì I saw you're hiring a marketing team. I created a cheat sheet on how to onboard new marketing hires quickly. Would love to hear your feedback.


TEMPLATE 12: Local Business Outreach
Structure:
Hey {{first_name}} ‚Äì [competitor 1] or [competitor 2] seem to be the closest choices. 

Are you thinking about ways to make the choice easier?
When to Use:
Presenting choice between two options
Existing solution vs new innovative alternative
Prospects aware of current methods but considering upgrades
Why It Works:
Immediately presents choice, creating curiosity
Acknowledges prospect's current situation
Introduces potentially better alternative
Asks open-ended question encouraging reflection
Brief and to-the-point
Easily customized for various industries
Example:
Subject: Clay table or traditional methods?

Hey {{first_name}} ‚Äì continuing with traditional lead management or upgrading to a Clay table with Slack integration for instant notifications seem to be your choices. Are you thinking about how to make the choice easier and increase conversions with warm calling?

Best,
%Signature%


TEMPLATE 13: Challenge of Similar Companies
Structure:
Personalization, 
challenge of others in the industry, 
solution, 
CTA.
When to Use:
Establishing credibility quickly
Creating urgency with industry challenges
B2B outreach with quantifiable pain points and clear ROI
Why It Works:
Starts with personalization
Establishes credibility by mentioning work with similar professionals
Presents specific, quantifiable challenges
Offers clear solution with concrete benefits
Includes CTA as question
Postscript adds personal touch and industry understanding
Example:
Hey Patrick,

We are working with a lot of security officers at banks who faced losses of $9K per hour due to ransomware and had phishing victims every 11 seconds.

We have a global team of experts available 24/7 to respond to and contain cyber incidents and can react in hours not days. When is the last time you tested your plan?

Cheers,

P. PS: I would attach a link but we both work in securityüòÖ


TEMPLATE 14: Do the Math
Structure:
Trigger: The reason for reaching out. 

Quick pitch: Short explanation of the impact. 

Calculation: Back-of-napkin calculation. 

CTA.
When to Use:
Specific, quantifiable data about prospect's business available
Clear, measurable impact can be demonstrated
B2B companies with quantifiable pain points
Potential financial impact is substantial
Why It Works:
Structure (Trigger, Quick Pitch, Calculation, CTA) creates compelling narrative that quickly captures attention, demonstrates value, provides clear reason to engage. Particularly suitable for data-driven decision-makers.
Example:
Mary, noticed you have over 50 open positions on your job portal.

We help tech scale ups reduce their new employee churn from 30% to 10% or less.

With a typical cost of mishire around $30,000 per employee, this would mean going from 15 mishires to 5, resulting in $300,000 saved.

Worth a chat?


TEMPLATE 15: Leverage Content in Outbound
Structure:
"[here is "value offering] hope it was helpful"

Hi [first name], 

`[insert name of content][how it helps].

Can I send it over to you?

[first name]

PS - Thought this was relevant because _____
When to Use:
Valuable, relevant resource directly addresses prospect's challenges/goals
Industries where sharing knowledge provides immediate value
Sales, marketing, sustainability, healthcare, education
Why It Works:
Follows "give before you ask" principle, offering immediate value. Personalized, concise, creates curiosity. Structure allows easy customization across industries. PS section adds context and shows research.
Example:
Hey Jason - we've compiled a cheat sheet on how folks like [social proof] are getting their AE's self-sourcing more than 30% of their own pipeline.

Can I send it over to you?

Ethan

PS - Thought this was relevant because I saw you recently decreased our SDR headcount and are hiring 3 more AEs right now.


TEMPLATE 16: Selling Software to Sales
Structure:
{{firstname}}, 

If [your value prop] is missing, then [technical pain]. 

As a result, [qualitative business impact]. 

This strategy causes [quantitative business impact]. 

[validating question]
When to Use:
Creating urgency by highlighting critical gap in current strategy/system
Decision-makers where real-time data and quick responses are crucial
SaaS, healthcare, e-commerce, education technology
Why It Works:
Creates urgency with problem-consequence-impact structure. Identifies missing element, explains immediate technical consequence, followed by qualitative and quantitative business impacts. Concludes with open-ended question.
Example:
John, If the KPI monitoring piece is missing you won't be able to see how your reps execute the strategy in real-time. As a result, you will only learn about success or failure when the monthly pipeline & revenue reports come in. It's a hit-or-miss strategy that can cost crucial ARR that is needed for the next funding round.

What are your thoughts?


TEMPLATE 17: Reviews
Structure:
Hey {{first_name}} ‚Äì I saw the great review {{name}} left about [AI summary of review].

Are you thinking about ways to keep the great reviews coming?

We're helping companies like {{company}} achieve [outcome] in [timeframe] without [no good rotten thing].

Would this be something you're looking to solve as well?
When to Use:
Businesses relying heavily on customer reviews/feedback
Industries where rapid response times significantly impact satisfaction
E-commerce, healthcare, education, service-based businesses
Why It Works:
Leverages social proof (positive review) and addresses common pain point (improving response times). Structure allows customization while maintaining focus on benefits of quick engagement. Versatile across sectors.
Example:
Subject: Fast replies = 50% boost in conversions?

Hey {{first_name}} ‚Äì I saw a note in Smartlead that mentioned fast replies are boosting conversion rates by 50%. Are you thinking about ways to keep your conversion rates climbing even higher?

We're helping companies like {{company}} achieve faster lead engagement and increased conversions without any manual follow-up headaches.

Would this be something you're looking to solve as well?

Best,
%Signature%


